Breaking News 



Lehigh County Judge William E. Ford stepping down







Contributed photo / The Morning Call
Judge William E. Ford. /(Ed. Note: LOCAL)
Judge William E. Ford. /(Ed. Note: LOCAL) (Contributed photo / The Morning Call)

Laurie Mason SchroederContact ReporterOf The Morning Call

Longtime Lehigh County judge stepping down.




After 24 years of hoisting a gavel, Lehigh County Judge William E. Ford has decided to step down from the bench.The 64-year-old Allentown Republican will leave his post at the end of the year to open his own law firm in Center City, focusing on civil litigation, mediation and estate law."It's been wonderful," Ford said, "but I feel that I'm ready for a new challenge. As a judge, I see all areas of the law. When I see an area that I haven't practiced, or see a lawyer coming up with a new solution to a problem, I think, 'Why haven't I tried that before?' I think it will be intellectually stimulating."Ford said he's also motivated by all the growth in downtown Allentown, and believes there's room for more attorneys there.

"It's all very exciting and I want to be a part of it," he said.During his tenure, Ford worked in all four divisions of the court — civil, criminal, family and orphans court. He currently oversees criminal court and adoption hearings.Ford was elected in 1991 and retained for 10-year terms in 2001 and 2011. He submitted his resignation to Gov. Tom Wolf on Monday, and is leaving four years into his current term.Ford's departure will leave a vacancy on the bench that can only be filled by gubernatorial appointment, since it comes too late for a special election. The state's current budget impasse makes an appointment unlikely, said Kerry R. Turtzo, the county's deputy district court administrator.

"We've heard throughout the state that it's just not happening," he said.Ford's announcement coincides with Senior Judge Lawrence J. Brenner's exit. Brenner must step down because he's reached the mandatory senior judge retirement age of 78, Turtzo said.Turtzo said other judges will take over Ford's caseload, and a senior jurist from Philadelphia, Judge John L. Braxton, has committed to spending one week each month in Lehigh to hear cases."It's going to be lean," Turtzo said.Ford said he's going to miss wearing the black robe. Being a judge was satisfying, he said, especially when he had the opportunity to help someone who came before him."Judges are in a position to correct things, and to right a wrong. When that happens, it's very rewarding," he said.Ford said he hopes to emulate the attorneys he's observed from the bench who are caring champions."Working with lawyers who truly care about their clients has been a highlight of my career," he said. "A caring attitude really helps achieve the best result in a case."He said he'll miss the courthouse staff, which he called the "most professional" in the region.A graduate of DeSales University, Ford received his law degree from the Dickinson School of Law in 1975. He has lectured at DeSales, Muhlenberg and Chestnut Hill colleges.Ford served as a captain in the Judge Advocate General's Corps of the Marine Reserve from 1975 to 1979. He was a county prosecutor from 1979 to 1991.He is a former basketball coach for the Catholic Youth Organization and former baseball coach for the West End Youth Association, and has been involved in numerous other civic organizations and charities.Ford and his wife, Rosemary, have 11 children, who range in age from 25 to 43 years old. He said the family is very excited about his next career move."Everyone has offered to help. We're all very energized," he said.lmason@mcall.comTwitter @LehighCourts610-820-6506

